content:
A range takes a number or text value and assigns it to groups that you've defined. You can use data numeric ranges in calculation matrices and by collating by alphabetic ranges.

For example, if age is a component of your pricing, you can use a numeric range to map the applicant's age to the correct age group:

17 or younger: Age Group 0
18 to 24: Age Group 1
25 to 29: Age Group 2
30 to ...: ...

When you configure numeric ranges for a matrix, values below the lowest level that you configure are treated as the lowest value, and values above the highest value that you configure are treated as the highest value configured for the matrix.

You can also collate by alphabetic ranges. For instance, to assign Contacts into one of three buckets by last name, you would create groups such as:

A-D: Bucket 1
E-K: Bucket 2
L-Z: Bucket 3

Additional dimensions in a matrix require additional rows.
title: Ranges in Calculation Matrices
